You can use the Blob and URL.createObjectURL methods in JavaScript to create a downloadable file. Here's an example function that saves text as a local file:

```
function saveTextAsFile(filename, content) {
  // Create a new Blob object with the specified content and MIME type
  var blob = new Blob([content], {type: "text/plain"});

  // Create a temporary URL for the Blob object
  var url = window.URL.createObjectURL(blob);

  // Create an anchor element to download the file
  var link = document.createElement("a");
  link.href = url;
  link.download = filename;

  // Append the anchor element to the body and click it to trigger the download
  document.body.appendChild(link);
  link.click();

  // Remove the anchor element from the body and revoke the temporary URL
  document.body.removeChild(link);
  window.URL.revokeObjectURL(url);
}
```

You can call this function with a filename and content string like so:

```
saveTextAsFile("example.txt", "This is some example text");
```

This will trigger a download of an example.txt file containing the specified text.
